    <p>This step by step tutorial will teach you how you can use silk router to achieve this.</p>
    <br/>
    <p>Implementation is fairly straight forward.</p>
    <b>Step 1:</b>
    <p>We have set <code>data-route</code> attribute to button as well as collapse section. We will use this attribute to set the page route.</p>
    <p>This tutorial demonstrates <code>hash</code> routing. Hash routes start with a <code>#</code> symbol followed by path.</p>
    <pre>
        <code>
    &lt;button ... data-route="<b>#/accordion1</b>"&gt;...&lt;/button&gt;</code>
    </pre>
    <p>The three routes we need to set are: <code>#/accordion1</code>, <code>#/accordion2</code>, and <code>#/accordion3</code>.</p>
    <b>Step 2:</b>
    <p>Add a click event listener to buttons</p>
    <pre>
        <code>
    $('.btn-link').on('click', function (e) {
        if ($(this).attr('aria-expanded') === 'true') {
            e.stopPropagation();
        } else {
            router.set($(this).data('route'), <b>false, true</b>);
        }
    });</code>
    </pre>
    <p>The <code>set</code> method accepts three parameters. The first parameter is the route string. The second parameter is the <code>replaceMode</code> flag. With <code>replaceMode</code> set to <code>false</code>, silk router will allow creating new history entries. The third parameter is a <code>noTrigger</code> flag. No trigger tells the router to skip calling the handler function this time.</p>
    <p>In our case, we want to skip the function call because bootstrap collapse handles the expand animation by itself. Our only role is to maintain the state of accordion when the page refreshes.</p>
    <b>Step 3:</b>
    <p>Maintain the current state of accordion when user refreshes the page.</p>
    <pre>
        <code>
    route(function (data) {
        if (<b>/accordion/</b>.test(data.route) && data.hash) {
            $('.btn-link')
                .attr('aria-expanded', false)
                .filter(`[data-route="${<b>data.route</b>}"]`)
                .attr('aria-expanded', true);
            $('.collapse')
                .removeClass('show')
                .filter(`[data-route="${<b>data.route</b>}"]`)
                .addClass('show');
        }
    });</code>
    </pre>
    <p>We have registered a generic handler to handle such type of routing. A generic handler listens to all types of route changes.</p>
